source":["# cnn_history = cnn_model.fit(\n","#     train_data,\n","#     epochs=3,\n","#     validation_data=test_data\n","# )"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":7,"id":"b54fa9fd","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.execute_input":"2026-05-26T18:56:24.396136Z","iopub.status.busy":"2026-05-26T18:56:24.395224Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-05-26T18:56:24.39944Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-05-26T18:56:24.398626Z"},"papermill":{"duration":0.013905,"end_time":"2026-05-26T18:56:24.401078+00:00","exception":false,"start_time":"2026-05-26T18:56:24.387173+00:00","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"outputs":[],"source":["# mlp_loss, mlp_acc = mlp_model.evaluate(test_data)\n","# cnn_loss, cnn_acc = cnn_model.evaluate(test_data)"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"1860633f","metadata":{"papermill":{"duration":0.006588,"end_time":"2026-05-26T18:56:24.414473+00:00","exception":false,"start_time":"2026-05-26T18:56:24.407885+00:00","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"source":["# LeNet\n","\n","LeNet is one of the earliest and most important **Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs)**. It was developed by Yann LeCun and colleagues in 1998 for handwritten digit recognition. It became famous for recognizing ZIP code digits and bank check numbers.\n","\n","**Historical Background**\n","\n","Before LeNet:\n","\n","* Traditional machine learning required manual feature extraction.\n","* Computers struggled with image recognition.\n","\n","LeNet introduced:\n","\n","* Automatic feature extraction using convolution\n","* End-to-end learning from images\n","\n","This became the foundation of modern deep learning in computer vision.\n","\n","**Legacy of LeNet**\n","\n","LeNet inspired many famous CNNs:\n","\n","* AlexNet\n","* VGGNet\n","* ResNet\n","\n","## Why LeNet Was Revolutionary\n","\n","LeNet introduced:\n","\n","| Innovation          | Importance         |\n","| ------------------- | ------------------ |\n","| Convolution         | Feature extraction |\n","| Weight sharing      | Fewer parameters   |\n","| Pooling             | Spatial reduction  |\n","| End-to-end learning | Automatic learning |\n","\n","These ideas are still used today.\n","\n","## Main Goal of LeNet\n","\n","LeNet was designed to classify handwritten digits:\n","\n","| Input        | Output  |\n","| ------------ | ------- |\n","| Image of \"3\" | Class 3 |\n","| Image of \"7\" | Class 7 |\n","\n","**MNIST Dataset**\n","\n","It was mainly trained on the famous handwritten digit dataset: MNIST(Modified National Institute of Standards and Technology)\n","\n","The dataset contains:\n","\n","* 60,000 training images\n","* 10,000 test images\n","* Digits from 0–9\n","\n","## LeNet-5 Architecture\n","\n","| Layer  | Name                  | Type                             | Kernel / Pool    | Stride | Output Size | Activation  | Parameters | Purpose                                           |\n","| ------ | --------------------- | -------------------------------- | ---------------- | ------ | ----------- | ----------- | ---------- | ------------------------------------------------- |\n","| Input  | Input Image           | —                                | —                | —      | 32×32×1     | —           | 0          | Raw grayscale image                               |\n","| C1     | Convolution           | Conv                             | 5×5, 6 filters   | 1      | 28×28×6     | Tanh        | 156        | Edge + simple feature extraction                  |\n","| S2     | Subsampling           | Average Pool (trainable)         | 2×2              | 2      | 14×14×6     | Tanh        | 12         | Downsampling + smoothing                          |\n","| C3     | Convolution           | Conv (partial connectivity)      | 5×5, 16 filters  | 1      | 10×10×16    | Tanh        | 2,416     | Higher-level feature extraction (shapes/textures) |\n","| S4     | Subsampling           | Average Pool (trainable)         | 2×2              | 2      | 5×5×16      | Tanh        | 32         | Spatial reduction                                 |\n","| C5     | Convolution (FC-like) | Conv (fully connected spatially) | 5×5, 120 filters | 1      | 1×1×120     | Tanh        | 48,120     | Global feature fusion (acts like FC)              |\n","| F6     | Fully Connected       | Dense                            | —                | —      | 84          | Tanh        | 10,164     | High-level decision features                      |\n","| Output | Classification Layer  | RBF / Softmax (variant)          | —                | —      | 10          | RBF/Softmax | 850        | Digit classification (0–9)                        |\n","\n","![CNN Architecture](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/masum184e/handbook-old/removed/images/cnn/lenet.png)\n","\n","> NB: S2 have 12 trainable (1 weight + 1 bias per map) parameters and S4 have 32 trainable parameters.\n","### Input Layer\n","\n","LeNet accepts grayscale images.\n","\n","Image size:\n","$$\n","32\\times32\\times1\n","$$\n","\n","Meaning:\n","\n","* Width = 32 pixels\n","* Height = 32 pixels\n","* 1 channel (grayscale)\n","\n","MNIST images are originally:\n","\n","$$\n","28\\times28\n","$$\n","\n","They are padded to:\n","\n","$$\n","32\\times32\n","$$\n","\n","for better convolution operations.\n","\n","### First Convolution Layer (C1)\n","\n","**Configuration**\n","\n","* Number of filters: 6\n","* Filter size:\n","$$\n","5\\times5\n","$$\n","* Stride = 1\n","* No padding\n","\n","**What Happens?**\n","\n","Each filter scans the image to detect patterns like:\n","\n","* edges\n","* curves\n","* corners\n","\n","### Activation Function\n","\n","LeNet originally used Tanh activation. Modern CNNs often use ReLU.\n","\n","### Pooling Layer (S2)\n","\n","LeNet orginally used Average Pooling. Modern CNNs mostly use Max Pooling.\n","\n","**Purpose of Pooling**\n","\n","* reduces image size\n","* reduces computation\n","* preserves important features\n","\n","### Second Convolution Layer (C3)\n","\n","Configuration:\n","\n","* 16 filters\n","* Filter size = 5×5\n","\n","Input:\n","\n","$$\n","14\\times14\\times6\n","$$\n","\n","Output:\n","$$\n","10\\times10\\times16\n","$$\n","\n","**What Does This Layer Learn?**\n","\n","This layer detects more complex patterns:\n","\n","* digit parts\n","* loops\n","* curves\n","* intersections\n","\n","Earlier layers learn simple edges. Deeper layers learn meaningful shapes.\n","\n","### Second Pooling Layer (S4)\n","\n","Input:\n","\n","$$\n","10\\times10\\times16\n","$$\n","\n","After pooling:\n","\n","$$\n","5\\times5\\times16\n","$$\n","\n","### Convolution Layer (C5)\n","\n","* Applies **120 filters of size 5×5**\n","* Output: **1×1×120**\n","\n","**Why it is special:**\n","\n","* Input is 5×5, filter is 5×5 → output collapses to 1×1\n","* Each filter sees the **entire spatial region**\n","\n","So it behaves like:\n","\n","* A **fully connected layer over spatial features**\n","* But implemented as convolution\n","\n","**What it learns:**\n","\n","* High-level digit representations\n","* Complete shape patterns (like “3-ness”, “7-ness”)\n","\n","### Fully Connected Layer (F6)\n","\n","* Input: 120 values\n","* Output: 84 neurons\n","\n","**What it does:**\n","\n","* Combines high-level features\n","* Builds decision logic\n","\n","**Interpretation:**\n","\n","* This is where abstraction becomes class-relevant\n","* Similar digits get separated here\n","\n","### Output Layer (10 classes)\n","\n","* Output: 10 neurons (digits 0–9)\n","\n","**Original design:**\n","\n","* Often described as **RBF-like classifier**\n","* Later implementations use **Softmax**\n","\n","**What it does:**\n","\n","* Produces probability-like scores\n","* Highest value = predicted digit"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":8,"id":"6f4b8634","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.execute_input":"2026-05-26T18:56:24.42958Z","iopub.status.busy":"2026-05-26T18:56:24.428806Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-05-26T18:56:28.582404Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-05-26T18:56:28.581603Z"