"</pre>\n"],"text/plain":["\u001b[1m Non-trainable params: \u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;34m704\u001b[0m (2.75 KB)\n"]},"metadata":{},"output_type":"display_data"}],"source":["from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential\n","from tensorflow.keras.layers import Input, Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Flatten, Dense, Dropout, BatchNormalization\n","\n","# AlexNet Model\n","model = Sequential([\n","\n","    # Upscaling to 227×227 = ~50× more pixels. Dataset becomes slow + heavy in RAM\n","    Input(shape=(128, 128, 3)), \n","    \n","    # Block 1\n","    Conv2D(filters=96, kernel_size=(11, 11), strides=4, padding='same', activation='relu'),\n","    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(3, 3), strides=2),\n","    BatchNormalization(),\n","    # AlexNet used Local Response Normalization (LRN), not BatchNorm. Keras does not include LRN directly.\n","    # This is acceptable in modern implementations and usually performs better.\n","    # Use:`tf.nn.local_response_normalization()` inside a Lambda layer.\n","    # Lambda(lambda x: tf.nn.local_response_normalization(x))\n","\n","    # Block 2\n","    Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=(5, 5), padding='same', activation='relu'),\n","    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(3, 3), strides=2),\n","    BatchNormalization(),\n","\n","    # Block 3\n","    Conv2D(filters=384, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'),\n","    Conv2D( filters=384, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'),\n","    Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'),\n","\n","    # S5\n","    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(3, 3), strides=2),\n","\n","    Flatten(),\n","\n","    # FC6\n","    Dense(1024, activation='relu'),\n","    # D6\n","    Dropout(0.5),\n","    # AlexNet uses 4096 neuron, it can generate ~100M+ parameters which may crash memory\n","\n","    # FC7\n","    Dense(1024, activation='relu'),\n","    # D7\n","    Dropout(0.5),\n","\n","    # Output Layer\n","    Dense(10, activation='softmax') # AlexNet uses 1000, but cifar10 have 10 classes\n","])\n","\n","model.compile(\n","    optimizer='adam',\n","    loss='categorical_crossentropy',\n","    metrics=['accuracy']\n",")\n","\n","# Model Summary\n","model.summary()"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":14,"id":"dc7c42b4","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.execute_input":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.397583Z","iopub.status.busy":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.397098Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.40114Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.400241Z"},"papermill":{"duration":0.021474,"end_time":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.402791+00:00","exception":false,"start_time":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.381317+00:00","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"outputs":[],"source":["# history = model.fit(\n","#     train_ds,\n","#     epochs=3,\n","#     validation_data=test_ds\n","# )"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":15,"id":"01929f70","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.execute_input":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.43366Z","iopub.status.busy":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.432526Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.438018Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.436915Z"},"papermill":{"duration":0.023591,"end_time":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.440438+00:00","exception":false,"start_time":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.416847+00:00","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"outputs":[],"source":["# test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(test_ds)"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"913a732f","metadata":{"papermill":{"duration":0.014595,"end_time":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.470599+00:00","exception":false,"start_time":"2026-05-26T18:56:53.456004+00:00","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"source":["## Why AlexNet Performed So Well\n","\n","AlexNet succeeded because of:\n","\n","| Technique         | Contribution              |\n","| ----------------- | ------------------------- |\n","| Deep architecture | Better feature extraction |\n","| ReLU              | Faster learning           |\n","| GPUs              | Efficient computation     |\n","| Data augmentation | More robust model         |\n","| Dropout           | Reduced overfitting       |\n","\n","### Data Augmentation\n","\n","AlexNet used image augmentation:\n","\n","* flipping\n","* cropping\n","* rotation\n","\n","**Purpose:** Increase dataset diversity.\n","\n","This helps prevent overfitting.\n","\n","### GPU Training\n","\n","AlexNet was trained using GPUs instead of CPUs.\n","\n","This reduced training time dramatically.\n","\n","Without GPUs:\n","\n","* training deep CNNs would have been impractical.\n","\n","## Charecterstics\n","\n","### Advantages\n","\n","| Advantage                       | Explanation                       |\n","| ------------------------------- | --------------------------------- |\n","| High accuracy                   | Much better than previous methods |\n","| Deep feature learning           | Learns complex visual patterns    |\n","| GPU acceleration                | Faster training                   |\n","| Introduced modern CNN practices | Influenced future architectures   |\n","\n","### Limitations\n","\n","| Limitation                     | Explanation           |\n","| ------------------------------ | --------------------- |\n","| Large number of parameters     | Memory intensive      |\n","| Slow compared to modern models | Computationally heavy |\n","| Overfitting risk               | Needs regularization  |\n","\n","### AlexNet vs LeNet\n","\n","| Feature    | LeNet     | AlexNet  |\n","| ---------- | --------- | -------- |\n","| Year       | 1998      | 2012     |\n","| Dataset    | MNIST     | ImageNet |\n","| Depth      | Shallow   | Deep     |\n","| Activation | Tanh      | ReLU     |\n","| Input      | Grayscale | RGB      |\n","| Classes    | 10        | 1000     |\n","\n","# VGGNet\n","\n","VGGNet is a famous deep convolutional neural network developed by researchers at Visual Geometry Group at the University of Oxford. It was introduced in 2014 and became one of the most influential CNN architectures in deep learning history.\n","\n","**Historical Background**\n","\n","Before VGGNet:\n","\n","* CNN architectures were becoming deeper,\n","* but designs were complicated.\n","\n","VGGNet showed that:\n","\n","> Very deep networks with small filters can achieve excellent performance.\n","\n","Its design philosophy was:\n","\n","* simplicity\n","* depth\n","* uniform architecture\n","\n","**Versions of VGGNet**\n","\n","Popular versions:\n","\n","| Model | Layers    |\n","| ----- | --------- |\n","| VGG11 | 11 layers |\n","| VGG13 | 13 layers |\n","| VGG16 | 16 layers |\n","| VGG19 | 19 layers |\n","\n","The most famous is: VGG16\n","\n","## Why VGGNet Was Revolutionary\n","\n","VGGNet introduced several key ideas:\n","\n","| Innovation               | Importance                |\n","| ------------------------ | ------------------------- |\n","| Very deep CNN            | Improved feature learning |\n","| Small 3×3 filters        | Reduced parameters        |\n","| Uniform architecture     | Simpler design            |\n","| Deep feature hierarchies | Better abstraction        |\n","\n","## Main Idea of VGGNet\n","\n","Instead of large filters like 11×11 in AlexNet\n","\n","VGGNet uses:\n","$$\n","3\\times3\n","$$\n","filters everywhere.\n","\n","**ImageNet Competition**\n","\n","VGGNet performed extremely well in:\n","\n","* ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2014\n","* It achieved top-tier accuracy on: ImageNet\n","\n","which contains:\n","\n","* 1+ million images\n","* 1000 object classes\n","\n","### Why Small 3×3 Filters?\n","\n","Using multiple 3×3 convolutions gives benefits:\n","\n","Two 3×3 convolutions approximate a:\n","\n","$$\n","5\\times5\n","$$\n","\n","receptive field.\n","\n","Three 3×3 convolutions approximate a:\n","$$\n","7\\times7\n","$$\n","\n","receptive field.\n","\n","## VGG-16 Architecture\n","\n","| Layer   | Name            | Type    | Kernel / Pool    | Stride | Output Size | Activation | Parameters  | Purpose                                        |\n","| ------- | --------------- | ------- | ---------------- | ------ | ----------- | ---------- | ----------- | ---------------------------------------------- |\n","| Input   | Input Image     | —       | —                | —      | 224×224×3   | —          | 0           | Raw RGB image input                            |\n","| C1_1    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 64 filters  | 1      | 224×224×64  | ReLU       | 1,792       | Detect low-level edges and textures            |\n","| C1_2    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 64 filters  | 1      | 224×224×64  | ReLU       | 36,928      | Refine edge and texture features               |\n","| S1      | Max Pooling     | MaxPool | 2×2              | 2      | 112×112×64  | —          | 0           | Spatial downsampling                           |\n","| C2_1    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 128 filters | 1      | 112×112×128 | ReLU       | 73,856      | Learn more detailed patterns                   |\n","| C2_2    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 128 filters | 1      | 112×112×128 | ReLU       | 147,584     | Extract richer texture combinations            |\n","| S2      | Max Pooling     | MaxPool | 2×2              | 2      | 56×56×128   | —          | 0           | Reduce feature map size                        |\n","| C3_1    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 256 filters | 1      | 56×56×256   | ReLU       | 295,168     | Learn object parts and shapes                  |\n","| C3_2    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 256 filters | 1      | 56×56×256   | ReLU       | 590,080     | Build deeper spatial understanding             |\n","| C3_3    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 256 filters | 1      | 56×56×256   | ReLU       | 590,080     | Capture complex visual structures              |\n","| S3      | Max Pooling     | MaxPool | 2×2              | 2      | 28×28×256   | —          | 0           | Compress spatial information                   |\n","| C4_1    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 512 filters | 1      | 28×28×512   | ReLU       | 1,180,160   | Learn high-level object structures             |\n","| C4_2    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 512 filters | 1      | 28×28×512   | ReLU       | 2,359,808   | Detect semantic object components              |\n","| C4_3    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 512 filters | 1      | 28×28×512   | ReLU       | 2,359,808   | Improve object representation                  |\n","| S4      | Max Pooling     | MaxPool | 2×2              | 2      | 14×14×512   | —          | 0           | Reduce computation and retain semantics        |\n","| C5_1    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 512 filters | 1      | 14×14×512   | ReLU       | 2,359,808   | Capture advanced object concepts               |\n","| C5_2    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 512 filters | 1      | 14×14×512   | ReLU       | 2,359,808   | Learn class-specific features                  |\n","| C5_3    | Convolution     | Conv    | 3×3, 512 filters | 1      | 14×14×512   | ReLU       | 2,359,808   | Final deep feature extraction                  |\n","| S5      | Max Pooling     | MaxPool | 2×2              | 2      | 7×7×512     | —          | 0           | Convert feature maps to compact representation |\n","| FC6     | Fully Connected | Dense   | —                | —      | 4096        | ReLU       | 102,764,544 | Learn global feature relationships             |\n","| FC7     | Fully Connected | Dense   | —                | —      | 4096        | ReLU       | 16,781,312  | High-level decision reasoning                  |\n","| FC8     | Output Layer    | Dense   | —                | —      | 1000        | Softmax    | 4,097,000   | Classification into 1000 classes               |\n","\n","![CNN Architecture](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/masum184e/handbook-old/removed/images/cnn/vggnet.png)\n","\n","### Input Layer\n","\n","VGGNet uses standard ImageNet-sized inputs:\n","\n","$$\n","224 \\times 224 \\times 3\n","$$\n","\n","* RGB images\n","* Fixed input size (important for FC layers later)\n","\n","###